author = {Nighat Mir and Mohammad A.U. Khan and Mome Gul Hussain},
keywords = {Diabetes, retinopathy, image processing, detection, retinal damage, diagnostic algorithm, smart healthcare, mobile health solutions, health informatics},
abstract = {Cities are becoming smarter with an increased reliance on smart computing technology for overcoming the emerging urbanization challenges. Besides other infrastructural components, healthcare sector has to go through many changes in terms of acquiring, processing, and distribution of healthcare data. Many healthcare mobile solutions are designed to support elderly and rural patients, healthcare workers, and urban consultants. With the fast pace of urbanization comes the undue stress on some vital human organs, the most vital among them are the eyes. The focus of the research is related with monitoring the eye health in some adverse health conditions such as diabetes. The risk of related visual loss in people with diabetes is up to 25 times higher than the population not affected by diabetes. Visual impairment is therefore the most feared complication of diabetes. Diabetes can damage the retina, and the chances of this happening increase with the duration of the disease. Treatment can be given to arrest this damage and prevent loss of vision, but it must be applied at the right moment because once vision is lost, treatment is unlikely to restore it. Unfortunately, retinal damage can become sight-threatening without the patient being aware of it. Therefore patients with diabetes should be encouraged to have regular check-ups for diabetic retinopathy. With advanced communication technology information can be processed and communicated rapidly which shows how heathcare has turned smarter and faster. This research reviews the technology available for smartphone-based fundus photography and suggests further research to evaluate the effectiveness of these devices when dealing with diagnosing eye diseases. However, none of the devices are meant to replace traditional fundus cameras or rule out a trained health professional for diagnosis.}
